From these few examples it appears that nouns ending in the same letter have different plurals. Moreover, as the Greeks, beside a plural number, have also a dual by which they express two things, so the Abipones have two plurals, of which the one signifies more than one, the other many: thus Joalb, a man. Joalee, 01· Joaleena, some men. Joaliripi, many men. Ahepegalss a horse. Alzepega, some horses. Ah'epegeripi, many horses.
